description: From New Latin, from acanthus (“thorn”), (from Ancient Greek ἄκανθος (ákanthos)) + Ancient Greek πτερύγιον (pterúgion) diminutive of πτέρυξ (ptérux, “wing, fin”), from πτερόν (pterón, “feather, wing”).

entries.meaning: (zoology) Similar to an acanthopterygian.[First attested in the mid 19th century.]
(zoology) Any fish of the superorder Acanthopterygii.[First attested in the mid 19th century.]
